{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565634","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565634"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:29:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:29:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17829"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640475"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:17:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:17:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17829"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17829","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17829"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.83,0.03,0.04,0.09,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10543"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76206"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10543","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10543"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17829"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61710"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"188"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3180"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5658"},{"type":"tags","id":"9029"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24587"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25031"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76206","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76206"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with paranoid delusions. She believes her neighbours are plotting to kill her and has not eaten for three days due to fears of poisoning. She has lost 8 kg in weight. She refuses all treatment and wants to leave the hospital.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the key requirement for involuntary treatment under mental health legislation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Presence of mental illness or disorder AND risk of serious harm to self or others","Lack of decision-making capacity only","Refusal to accept voluntary treatment with a diagnosis of mental illness","Presence of any mental illness diagnosis OR risk of serious harm to self or others","Request from family members due to concern for harm to self or others"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe key requirement for involuntary treatment is the \u003Cstrong\u003Epresence of mental illness or disorder AND risk of serious harm to self or others\u003C/strong\u003E. Both components must be present - having a mental illness alone is insufficient grounds for involuntary treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELack of decision-making capacity only\u003C/strong\u003E - Capacity assessment is separate from involuntary treatment criteria. A person may have impaired capacity but not require involuntary treatment if there is no serious risk, or conversely may have capacity but still require involuntary treatment if criteria are met.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERefusal to accept voluntary treatment with a diagnosis of mental illness\u003C/strong\u003E - Treatment refusal alone, even with a mental illness diagnosis, is insufficient grounds for involuntary treatment without evidence of serious risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPresence of any mental illness diagnosis OR risk of serious harm to self or others\u003C/strong\u003E - Both components must be present together.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequest from family members due to concern for harm to self or others\u003C/strong\u003E - While family concerns are important considerations, they cannot override legal criteria which require both mental illness/disorder AND risk assessment by qualified clinicians.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe risk component typically includes risk of serious harm to self or others, or risk of serious deterioration in mental or physical health. Regular review is required to ensure involuntary treatment remains necessary and appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Involuntary treatment requires both mental illness or disorder AND serious risk of harm to self/others.","Capacity assessment is separate from involuntary treatment - a person can have capacity but still require involuntary treatment.","Involuntary treatment orders must be regularly reviewed and are time-limited under mental health legislation."],"references":["Involuntary commitment and treatment criteria in Australia and New Zealand Mental Health acts. The Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Psychiatrists. Available from: https://www.ranzcp.org/getmedia/f85985d3-6484-4275-a862-a3d39a517685/involuntary-commitment-and-treatment-laws.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61710"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17829"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61710"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-02T12:49:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T12:49:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10543"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76206"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"